Project 2: Image Homography and Warping¶

Part 1: Image Homography Estimation¶

The homography transformation effectively removed the perspective distortion from the angled poster, making it appear as if the photo were taken straight on. By manually selecting four corner points, a 33 homography matrix H was calculated using the Direct Linear Transform (DLT) algorithm. Applying inverse warping with H^-1 produced the rectified image, restoring the true rectangular proportions of the surface.

Homography works because it mathematically defines a mapping between two planar views under perspective projection. Since the poster is a flat surface, its perspective distortion can be corrected perfectly. This concept is widely used in real-world applications such as document scanning, augmented reality, planar surface alignment, and texture mapping in computer vision.

Part 2: Creative Application (Exploration and Extension)¶

For this part, I used homography to create an augmented-reality effect by projecting a new image onto the same tilted poster from Part 1. Using the same corner points, the overlay was warped to match the exact perspective of the surface so that it looked naturally integrated into the scene. The idea was to test how accurately a planar transformation could anchor digital content in a real environment.

What worked best was how precisely the homography aligned the overlay once the points were tuned. The result looked convincing, with straight edges and realistic depth, showing how a single transformation matrix can lock an image onto a surface as if it were really printed there. The 2 main challenges were lighting differences that made the overlay stand out and coordinate errors that caused drift and stretching. Getting both geometry and tone to feel consistent took some trial and error.

Part 3: Warping Comparison¶

Two image warping techniques were applied to the same set of facial landmarks to evaluate how each method handles localized and global deformations. Both methods use the same control points but approach deformation differently.

  • Triangular Mesh Warping applies local affine transformations within each triangle formed by the control points. This gives it fine-grained control over specific regions of the image, which makes it fast and predictable. However, because each triangle is transformed independently, there can be visible seams or discontinuities where adjacent triangles dont align perfectly. This behavior is most noticeable around sharp features such as the nose or jawline, where abrupt local differences can make the warp look slightly segmented or cut. Despite that, its efficient and performs well in real-time systems where localized edits or animations are needed.

  • Thin-Plate Spline (TPS), on the other hand, treats the entire deformation as a smooth, continuous function by minimizing bending energy across the image. It doesnt treat triangles separately, but rather models the deformation globally, ensuring that movement at one landmark gradually influences nearby areas. This produces smoother and more natural-looking results, especially for organic surfaces like human faces. The trade-off is that TPS is computationally more expensive and sometimes over-smooths regions that need sharper control, such as corners or edges.

In practice, the triangular mesh warp tends to preserve structure and sharpness at the cost of continuity, while TPS excels in producing visually coherent and realistic transformations across the entire surface. For applications like facial animation or shape morphing, TPS is generally preferred because of its smoothness and fluid motion, whereas the triangular mesh approach remains a strong choice for interactive systems, AR filters, or localized adjustments that dont require full-frame smoothing. In this part, the difference between the two methods was clear. The triangular mesh warp introduced small discontinuities around high-contrast features, while the TPS deformation appeared smoother and more cohesive. TPS produced a more natural transformation that resembled real facial movement, while the triangular mesh felt stiffer but more controlled. Together, these results highlight the tradeoff between computational speed and visual realism when performing non-rigid image warping.
